We identified 9 149 030 admissions which underwent the defined surgical procedures between 1998 and 2007, representing a national estimate of 44 793 273 patient admissions. Of those, 5.48% had a diagnosis of obesity. The incidence of RI/ARDS was 1.82% among patients with obesity and 2.01% (P < .0001) among those without the diagnosis. Table 1
details patient and health-care system-related demographics of patients with the diagnosis of RI/ARDS by obesity status. Among other differences, obese patients tended to be younger and more likely female compared to their nonobese counterparts. Hospital admissions for obese patients were more likely of an urgent but less likely of an emergent nature compared to nonobese patients. The average comorbidity burden was higher among patients with obesity (Deyo index 1.38 [1.35; 1.40] vs 0.89 [0.89; 0.90], P < .0001), which was reflected in the higher rates of comorbidities such as previous myocardial infarction, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and diabetes (Figure 1
). Patients with obesity whose postoperative course was complicated by RI/ARDS had a significantly lower incidence of the need for mechanical ventilation (50% vs 55%, P < .0001). In-hospital mortality was significantly lower compared to nonobese patients (5.45% vs 18.72%, P < .0001; Figure 2
). For those patients with RI/ARDS requiring intubation, the in-hospital mortality rate was 11% for obese and 25% for nonobese patients, respectively (P < .0001). In comparison, in-hospital mortality among all patients in our data set was 2.42%, and 2.10% among all those who did not developed RI/ARDS.
